  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Montgomery's Walk-Off Hit Lifts White Sox Over Royals",
    "subheadline": "Chicago White Sox 2, Kansas City Royals 1.",
    "lead_angle": "Braden Montgomery slapped a clean single through the left side of the infield, sending the winning run home from third and giving the Chicago White Sox a 2-1 walk-off victory over the Kansas City Royals. The knock came in the bottom of the ninth off reliever Daniel Lynch IV, who couldn't strand the runner. Players spilled from the home dugout at Rate Field to mob Montgomery, capping a tense divisional duel that was deadlocked for most of the night.\n\nFor six frames, the game was a pitcher's showcase. The stalemate finally broke in the top of the seventh when Kansas City manufactured a run on a sacrifice fly. But the White Sox punched right back in their half. Chase Meidroth led off with a double and was driven in two batters later by a Colson Montgomery single to knot the score. That immediate answer reset the board and turned the final innings into a battle of bullpens.\n\nBraden Montgomery was the man of the hour, finishing 2-for-4 with the game's lone RBI for Chicago. His final swing settled a contest where runs were a precious commodity. The victory, credited to Grant Taylor after a scoreless top of the ninth, nudges the White Sox further ahead of their rivals in a tight American League Central race. For the Royals, it was a bitter defeat that wasted a perfect 2-for-2 day from Michael Massey.",
    "reason": "Walk-offs are baseball's signature drama. The season's best finish this day."
  },
